sect2.para:
Despite OCD onset being most common in adolescence (mean age of onset = 16.9 years; Brakoulias et al., 
            2017
         ), intrusive thoughts and compulsions can appear during early childhood between ages 5 and 7 (Garcia et al., 
            2009
         ). Although older adults may present with OCD symptoms, the onset of their symptoms is likely to have started in childhood/young adulthood and progressed as they aged (Grenier et al., 
            2009
         ).

Ethnically/racially minoritized groups are often unrepresented and understudied in OCD research, which increases the risk of misdiagnosis and cultural insensitivity in clinical practice. According to Williams et al. (
            2020
         ), clinicians who are unfamiliar with different cultural backgrounds may inadvertently convey through their words or actions disrespect, insensitivity, or discrimination. For instance, clinicians may hold stereotypes about how people of color cope and what types of presenting
            presenting
          concerns they report, resulting in misdiagnosis or avoidance of discussion of OCD symptoms when clinically indicated (Williams et al., 
            2020
         ). Furthermore, African Americans with OCD are more likely to be misdiagnosed with other disorders, such as psychosis, as a result of culturally specific explanations for their symptomology. Additionally, Latinos continue to be underrepresented in clinical trials for OCD, which may be due to a reluctance to participate in psychological treatment and/or research. Latinos may be hesitant to seek help for their OCD symptoms due to cultural stigma, attribution of symptoms to somatic reasons, socioeconomic barriers, or fears that clinicians may misunderstand their concerns due to limited education on cultural norms/differences (Wetterneck et al., 
            2012
         ).

Given that minoritized populations are less likely to seek treatment than their White counterparts, it is important that mental health providers disseminate psychoeducation in these communities to decrease stigma and provide an accurate description of what symptoms are consistent with an OCD diagnosis. Mental health providers can adapt their recruitment efforts to ensure minoritized communities are able to receive accurate diagnostic assessment and treatment, such as having fliers for psychological services in various languages, providing affordable assessment and treatment options (i. e., financial compensation with clinical trials, sliding scale option), and having flexible appointment slots that accommodate families’ work schedules (Wetterneck et al.,
            2012
         ). Multiple marginalized identities (i. e., race, gender, sexuality) can also lead to greater OCD symptom severity, as individuals may experience greater symptoms of depression and lower quality of life during treatment and after discharge compared to their more privileged counterparts (Wadsworth et al.,
            2020
         ). Throughout the diagnostic process, it is important for clinicians to be mindful of patients’ ethnic/racial and intersecting identities.
